               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184210240154"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18421024-name-995" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18421024-name-995" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421024-name-995" type="surname" value="DAWSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421024-name-995" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM DAWSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am groom to Peter Smith, of North-bank. On the 7th of October I put a coat into the housekeeper's room—I saw it safe at ten o'clock in the morning, it was missed in the evening—this is it—it is my master's.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18421024-name-996" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18421024-name-996" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421024-name-996" type="surname" value="ANDERSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421024-name-996" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES ANDERSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I was on the coach-rank—the prisoner came and asked me what I charged to go to Westminster Abbey—I said half-a-crown—I took him in—he had this coat on—I went on a little further—I could see no policeman—I turned round in a short time, and the coat was off him—I then stopped, and said I did not like my job, I would not take him—he opened the door and jumped out—I got off and took him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I met a young man with a bundle and this coat; he said, "If you will take this to Westminster Abbey I will give you 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>." I did not intend to thieve the coat, I had not a farthing.</p>
